        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Dec 22 1875</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am much obliged to you for so kindly writing to me.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I am curious to hear about the feathers, but I am in no hurry. I will therefore wait &amp; see whether Mr Sorby’s paper appears;<ref target="#foot.f2"/> if not, I will write to him—</p>
<p>With many thanks | yours sincerely | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10310.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from G. G. Stokes, 20 December 1875</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Stokes had told CD that <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4469.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Henry Clifton Sorby</ref> had determined the cause of the play of colours in the feathers of peacocks and humming-birds (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10310.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from G. G. Stokes, 20 December 1875</ref>).</note>
        </div>        
            
